I haven't been very consistent in updating [my micro.blog bookshelf](https://micro.andrewbelfield.com/bookshelf/). Here are the books I've read since the spring semester ended in mid May:

- *Francis & Bonaventure* (Paul Rout);
- *Women of the Streets: Early Franciscan Women & their Mendicant Vocation* (Darleen Pryds);
- *The Theological & Ecological Vision of Laudato si': Everything Is Connected* (Vincent J. Miller, editor);
- *Confessions* (Augustine of Hippo, translated by R.S. Pine-Coffin);
- *Storyland: A New Mythology of Britain* (Amy Jeffs);
- *Enduring Presence: Diversity & Authenticity among the First Generations of Franciscan Laity* (Darleen Pryds);
- *Blood Theology: Seeing Red in Body- & God-Talk* (Eugene F. Rogers, Jr.);
- *Touch the Wounds: On Suffering, Trust, & Transformation* (Tomás Halík);
- *Nocturnes for the King of Naples* (Edmund White);
- *Pilgrim at Tinker Creek* (Annie Dillard);
- *Countries of Origin: A Novel* (Javier Fuentes); &
- *The Winter's Tale* (William Shakespeare).

Fun question from Twitter: what author do you have the most pages of writing by (i.e., takes up the most space on a shelf)? 📚

Looking around at my office, I think my top five are:

1. [Bonaventure](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bonaventure);
2. [Thomas Merton](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Thomas_Merton);
3. [Alexander of Hales](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Alexander_of_Hales) (so long as you include [his school](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Alexander_of_Hales#Summa_Universae_Theologiae));
4. [School of St. Victor](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/School_of_Saint_Victor); &
5. [Augustine](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Augustine_of_Hippo).
